data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws.** The entire cooperative-abort model is gone.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be raised** — that `catch` block is dead code.

The idiomatic .NET 8 replacement uses `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation and `Task`-based patterns instead of raw threads.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful shutdown, with a timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — it's stuck in unmanaged code
            // or an uncancellable call. Log a warning; there is no safe
            // equivalent of Abort() in .NET 8.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Monitor.Wait` or unmanaged I/O, cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** refactor it to accept a `CancellationToken` (e.g., use `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(token)` or async I/O). |
| **No forced termination exists** | There is no .NET 8 equivalent of `Abort()`. If code is truly stuck, your only option is process-level termination. Design all blocking operations to be cancellable. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | The old `_running` flag can't interrupt a blocking `GetNextItem()`. `CancellationToken` solves this — it can unblock `WaitHandle`-based waits and throw into async calls. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in Stop()** | Replaced with `await Task.WhenAny(...)` — non-blocking, with a real timeout. |
| **Exception filter matters** | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` distinguishes intentional cancellation from unexpected exceptions. Without the `when` filter, you'd swallow bugs. |
| **Dispose pattern** | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`. Failing to dispose it leaks callback registrations. |

### If You Need IHostedService (ASP.NET / Worker Service)

For hosted apps, prefer `BackgroundService` which handles the lifecycle for you:

```csharp
public class MyWorker : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item);
        }
    }
}
```

Register with `builder.Services.AddHostedService<MyWorker>()`. The host manages start/stop and passes the cancellation token automatically.
